# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-anti-vivisection-society
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] Alfred Owen Broadley was born on 7 July 1868 in Greetland, Yorkshire, to Owen and Elizabeth Broadley.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He was baptised on 6 September at St Thomas, Greetland.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] Broadley began his minister career with the Bible Christian Church at Salford from 1905 to 1917.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He was assistant preacher to James Clark at Cross Lane Church in Salford.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He worked as an engraver at Broad Oak Printworks.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He was appointed minister at Haliwell Road Unitarian Church in Bolton from 1918 to 1922.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He was minister of the Free Christian Church in Leicester and of Dover Unitarian Church from 1933 to 1939.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He joined the Vegetarian Society in 1894 and became their lecturer in 1897.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He advocated for a vegetarian diet consisting of whole bread, nuts, soups, omelettes, coffee and fruit.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] In 1912, Broadley was a speaker at Vegetarian Society meeting in Plymouth with Alfred B.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He commented that he had been a vegetarian for 21 years which had made him a happier man without visit to a doctor.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He also lectured on "Vegetarianism and the Higher Life", expounding the thesis that "any relationship to living creatures not based upon love, is contrary to conscience and will of God".
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] Broadley conducted the memorial service for William E.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] Axon's funeral at St Paul's Church, Kersal Moor in January 1913.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] He was a delegate of the Vegetarian Society to the Fourth Congress of the International Vegetarian Union in June 1913.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] Broadley was an opponent of vivisection.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] In 1923, he attended an anti-vivisection meeting with members from the British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection in Preston.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] Broadley died on 25 April 1939 from a heart attack at his residence in Dover, aged 70.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-o-broadley] His funeral was held at St James's Cemetery.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] Wall was the son of Abiathar Brown Wall, a physician of Bayswater.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He was educated at St Bartholomew's Hospital and studied surgery at London Hospital.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He also studied medicine at Edinburgh University.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] After he qualified he became an assistant to his father and took up an appointment in India where he resided for several years.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] Upon returning he settled at Thornton Avenue, Streatham Hill where he established his practice for 28 years.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] Wall was an advocate of animal welfare and a staunch opponent of vivisection.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He argued that animals especially vertebrates have mental faculties identical with those of man such as intelligence, memory and sympathy and as they are capable of intense suffering, we have no right to inflict such suffering.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] Wall was a member of the International Society for the Suppression of Vivisection.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] In 1881, Wall co-authored *Vivisection Scientifically and Ethically Considered in Prize Essays*, a collection of prize-winning essays exploring the ethics of vivisection.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] A prize of two hundred guineas was offered by an anonymous benefactor for the best essay against vivisection and seven judges were appointed to weigh the merits of the competitors.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] A review noted that the book presented "the case of the anti-vivisectionists clearly and strongly".
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He was a speaker on anti-vivisection and attended meetings throughout the United Kingdom and at congresses in Paris and Zurich.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] His 1892 paper at the Nottingham anti-vivisection congress was reprinted and translated.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He served on the committee of the London Anti-Vivisection Society and became its honorary treasurer and a trustee.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He was a co-founder of the National Anti-Vivisection Hospital and one of its first physicians.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He was a trustee of the hospital with Lord Coleridge, Lord Hatherton, Rev.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He treated over 100 patients a week at the hospital without fee or reward.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] In 1912, he became the first permanent chairman of the London and Provincial Anti-Vivisection Society Committee.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] He was also president of the Oxford Branch.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] Wall was a member of the British Medical Association.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] Sidney Trist described Wall as "the gentlest of critics, most generous in his commendation, absolutely unselfish, of unchallengeable loyalty and full of the spirit of forgiveness".
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/abiathar-wall] A memorial headstone was planned by Wall's friends in tribute of a "notable champion for the just and merciful treatment of animals".
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] The **American Anti-Vivisection Society** (**AAVS**) is a Jenkintown, Pennsylvania-based animal protectionism organization created with the goal of eliminating a number of different procedures done by medical and cosmetic groups in relation to animal cruelty in the United States.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] It seeks to help the betterment of animal life and human-animal interaction through legislation reform.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] It was the first anti-vivisection organization founded in the United States.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] The American Anti-Vivisection Society was founded by Caroline Earle White and Adele Biddle in 1883 in Philadelphia.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] The group was inspired by Britain's recently passed Cruelty to Animals Act 1876.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] Caroline White corresponded with Frances Power Cobbe, the woman who led the Victoria Street Society and had the Cruelty of Animals Act passed.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] The Society advocated complete abolition of vivisection in scientific testing.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] The AAVS launched leaflet campaigns, held marches and recruited legislative advocates.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] The first American animal testing facilities were opened in the 1860s and 1870s, much to the dismay of animal rights pioneers.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] The biggest concern of the AAVS was the implementation of vivisection in medical testing.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] Mark Twain's sketch "A Dog's Tale" was used by the Anti-Vivisection Society in its campaign against that practice.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] Additionally, it was issued by the British Anti-Vivisection Society as a pamphlet shortly after it was first published in *Harper's Magazine* in late 1903.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] In 1908, the AAVS tried to pass anti-vivisection legislation in Pennsylvania but was defeated by the "determination" of the medical profession.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] In the 1920s the AAVS sponsored a humane alternative to fur, a synthetic fur known as "humanifur".
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] The AAVS gained medical support but remained at odds with the American Medical Association (AMA), who argued that vivisection was critical to furthering medical advances.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] Anti-vivisectionists spent the next three decades trying to achieve legislation at state level but only succeeded on a national scale until the 1960s.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] Hunt president of the AAVS argued against regulation of vivisection and stated that the "American Anti-Vivisection Society stands, as it always has done, for abolition of vivisection on the ground that it is wrong, cruel and fruitless".
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] The AAVS has consistently worked on educating the public on issues regarding animal cruelty as well as worked with the U.S.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] Federal government in passing legislations for animal rights.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] The organization's earliest publication was a magazine created in 1892 entitled the *Journal of Zoöphily*.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] Mary Frances Lovell was its associate editor.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] The *Journal of Zoöphily* informed its readers of recent vivisection and animal protectionism issues.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] The magazine published articles about animal intelligence, "hero dogs" and the loyal character of animals.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] It noted that animal cruelty was a sign of the decline of morality in society.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] The publication changed its name a number of times, from *The Starry Cross* in 1922, *The A-V* in 1939, and resting finally with *AV Magazine* some years after that.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] Halvey secretary of the AAVS was managing editor of *The A-V* for 47 years.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] The AAVS has had radio programs, such as "Have You a Dog?" as well as occasional spots and commercials on radio and television.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] Animalearn was created in 1990 and is the AAVS' educational department.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] The group intends to illustrate how science and biology can be taught in schools without actually using animals, like with dissection in the classroom.
[src:american-anti-vivisection-society/american-anti-vivisection-society] Animalearn conducts free workshops with educators nationwide to show how to teach science without the use of animals, as well as trying to incorporate animal-rights, in concept and practice, into the curriculum and educational environment of the school setting.
